text:
For starters, if you wanna know if the game is F2P friendly. Yeah In some ways it is.

If you ever played princess connect, the gacha system is  kinda the same as PC is what I‚Äôm saying. There‚Äôs no ‚Äúpity‚Äù system but there‚Äôs a ‚Äúspark‚Äù system, you need 200 Recruitment points, to redeem a given student (only during a specific characters rate up banner.)
The rates are kinda iffy is the nicest way to put it 0.07% during rate up banners for the given 3* star unit.
That aside, game is quite nice since it gives you lots of Pyroxenes. And for newcomers it‚Äôs easy to Reroll your account. 
I‚Äôll say this, if you care about meta, you‚Äôll have some fun with that aspect of the game, lol. 

There‚Äôs a better comment here that‚Äôll inform you about the battle mechanics, if you wanna know more about that. But to simplify it, there‚Äôs various ‚Äústriker‚Äù class & ‚Äúdefense‚Äù type class based units.
And with that, there‚Äôs a rock, paper, ‚úÇÔ∏è formula because of these damage & defensive types.
Each character has 4 sets of skills to upgrade, & 3 gear slots to equip accessories like shoes, watches, bags etc etc that‚Äôll help give added bonuses to students. And of course each of these accessories also has their own materials to upgrade & level up. 

Other then that, the story portion of the game is a mix of comedy with some serious moments here & there.

text:
The game systems can be a bit confusing I reckon, it all makes sense once you play it for a bit though.

Remember that abilities can be aimed during a battle, by dragging (click and hold) the ability icon from the bottom right, into the battlefield: it slows down time, and lets you see the area affected by that ability.

The game can be played as a Free 2 Play, but in return you need to play it regularly and learn all their sub-systems:
- the Sensei XP level vs the students XP system (combat reports)
- the Equipment system (item drops + orbs)
- the Momo levels (Lessons system + Cafe)
- the Stamina/AP system (Cafe + PvP system)
- etc...

Initially Blue Archive was meant as combination of the usual waifu gacha, without much inputs - and X-Com, which is a legendary squad-management game series, where you give orders to your units to clear various levels of aliens.

In Blue Archive, the movement was made automatic to make it more accessible and avoid cheesing the enemy AI, so you're left with controlling their abilities: when and where you use them during a battle.

So unlike many gacha, the live gameplay is an important part of the game: you can't really ignore it, the proper use of an ability can really win or lose a battle.

That's why, when a level says "level 30 recommended", properly using abilities lets you clear it (with 3 stars) with level 20 students. Generally, a 10-level gap is possible for Story missions and most Quest (events) missions.

PS: if some event content is inaccessible to you, it's always possible to check it on YouTube...
